05147nam a22009375i 9780520950047DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20112011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020758978  a97805209500477 a10.1525/97805209500472doi  a(DE-B1597)520878  a(OCoLC)739104390  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA10aP306 4aP306b.T34 2011eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a418/.022221 aTageldin, Shaden M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisarming Words :bEmpire and the Seductions of Translation in Egypt /cShaden M. Tageldin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFlashPoints ;v50 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a book that radically challenges conventional understandings of the dynamics of cultural imperialism, Shaden M. Tageldin unravels the complex relationship between translation and seduction in the colonial context. She examines the afterlives of two occupations of Egypt—by the French in 1798 and by the British in 1882—in a rich comparative analysis of acts, fictions, and theories that translated the European into the Egyptian, the Arab, or the Muslim. Tageldin finds that the encounter with European Orientalism often invited colonized Egyptians to imagine themselves "equal" to or even "masters" of their colonizers, and thus, paradoxically, to translate themselves toward—virtually into—the European. Moving beyond the domination/resistance binary that continues to govern understandings of colonial history, Tageldin redefines cultural imperialism as a politics of translational seduction, a politics that lures the colonized to seek power through empire rather than against it, thereby repressing its inherent inequalities. She considers, among others, the interplays of Napoleon and Hasan al-'Attar; Rifa'a al-Tahtawi, Silvestre de Sacy, and Joseph Agoub; Cromer, 'Ali Mubarak, Muhammad al-Siba'i, and Thomas Carlyle; Ibrahim 'Abd al-Qadir al-Mazini, Muhammad Husayn Haykal, and Ahmad Hasan al-Zayyat; and Salama Musa, G. Elliot Smith, Naguib Mahfouz, and Lawrence Durrell. In conversation with new work on translation, comparative literature, imperialism, and nationalism, Tageldin engages postcolonial and poststructuralist theorists from Frantz Fanon, Edward Said, and Gayatri Spivak to Jean Baudrillard, Walter Benjamin, Emile Benveniste, and Jacques Derrida.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aComparative literaturexArabic and English. 0aComparative literaturexArabic and French. 0aComparative literaturexEnglishvCongresses. 0aComparative literaturexEnglish. 0aLanguage and languages in literature. 0aPostcolonialismzEgypt. 0aTranslating and interpretingzEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aTranslating and interpretingzEgyptxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a19th century egypt.  a19th century europe.  aarab and muslim.  abritish occupation of egypt.  acolonial history.  acolonized egyptians.  acultural imperialism.  aedward said.  aegyptian empire.  aegyptian history.  aeurope and egypt.  aeuropean colonialism.  aeuropean colonization.  aeuropean empire.  aeuropean orientalism.  afrantz fanon.  afrench occupation of egypt.  ahasan al-attar.  aimperialism and nationalism.  aimperialism.  ajacques derrida.  anapoleon.  apostcolonial egypt.  apostructuralist theorists.  atranslational seduction.  awalter benjamin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095004740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950047423